               <fo:inline font-style="italic">Reading from the Margins</fo:inline>. Ed. Nirin Abbas. Cranbury, NJ: Rosemount, 2003. 108-121. Print.</fo:block></fo:block><fo:block space-before="7pt" text-align="justify" start-indent="1pc" text-indent="1pc" font-size="11pt" line-height="16pt" font-family="Georgia">Strauss, Walter A. <fo:inline font-style="italic">Descent and Return: The Orphic Theme in Modern Literature</fo:inline>.</fo:block><fo:block space-before="7pt" text-align="justify" start-indent="1pc" text-indent="1pc" font-size="11pt" line-height="16pt" font-family="Georgia">Cambridge: Harvard University, 1971. Print.</fo:block><fo:block space-before="7pt" text-align="justify" start-indent="1pc" text-indent="1pc" font-size="11pt" line-height="16pt" font-family="Georgia">Woodruffe, John. âThe Science of Death.â <fo:inline font-style="italic">The Tibetan Book of the Dead</fo:inline>. Ed. W.Y.</fo:block><fo:block space-before="7pt" text-align="justify" start-indent="1pc" text-indent="1pc" font-size="11pt" line-height="16pt" font-family="Georgia">Evans-Wentz. Oxford: Oxford University, 2000. Print.</fo:block></fo:block></fo:block><fo:block margin-left="0em" font-family="Georgia" font-size="10pt" line-height="12pt" text-align="start" font-style="normal" font-weight="normal"><fo:block space-before="12pt" id="d7e1067"><fo:block start-indent="0pc" font-family="sans-serif" keep-with-next.within-page="always" font-size="14pt" line-height="16pt">End notes</fo:block><fo:block><fo:block space-before="4pt" id="d7e1069"><fo:inline><fo:basic-link font-family="sans-serif" font-size="85%" font-weight="normal" color="midnightblue" internal-destination="xr1" id="fn1">1</fo:basic-link></fo:inline>.   Following Eddinsâs example, I will attempt to separate the specific Judeo-Christian heresy from the general term, using a small âgâ for the latter.</fo:block></fo:block><fo:block><fo:block space-before="4pt" id="d7e1072"><fo:inline><fo:basic-link font-family="sans-serif" font-size="85%" font-weight="normal" color="midnightblue" internal-destination="xr2" id="fn2">2</fo:basic-link></fo:inline>.   A working definition of Gnostic religious principles: The attempt, through ritual and/or asceticism, to conquer or transcend âthis world,â a prison created by the Demiurge (Devil, <fo:inline font-style="italic">Satanil</fo:inline>) in order to trap the Divine Light in Material Darkness. All matter is evil and there is no contact with the Divineâthe fragment of the Divine trapped within us (spark, <fo:inline font-style="italic">pneuma</fo:inline>) strives to be reunited with the Alien God through destruction of or removal from the Natural Order, and achievement of <fo:inline font-style="italic">gnosis</fo:inline>, knowledge of God or knowledge of the way back to God. Organizations and institutions which participate in âthe systematic extirpation of the human [or natural] in the name of powerâ (Eddins 10) might be considered âgnosticâ in a secular sense, in their promotion of Death as a means of achieving their ends.</fo:block></fo:block><fo:block><fo:block space-before="4pt" id="d7e1084"><fo:inline><fo:basic-link font-family="sans-serif" font-size="85%" font-weight="normal" color="midnightblue" internal-destination="xr3" id="fn3">3</fo:basic-link></fo:inline>.   A âconsecration [of natural order and the symbiotic notion of cyclical return] [â¦] a counterreligion to the worship of mechanism, power, andâultimatelyâdeathâ (Eddins 5).</fo:block></fo:block><fo:block><fo:block space-before="4pt" id="d7e1087"><fo:inline><fo:basic-link font-family="sans-serif" font-size="85%" font-weight="normal" color="midnightblue" internal-destination="xr4" id="fn4">4</fo:basic-link></fo:inline>.   For a discussion of the novelâs construction as parody/pastiche, see Brian McHaleâs âGenre as History: Genre Poaching in <fo:inline font-style="italic">Against the Day.</fo:inline>â</fo:block></fo:block><fo:block><fo:block space-before="4pt" id="d7e1093"><fo:inline><fo:basic-link font-family="sans-serif" font-size="85%" font-weight="normal" color="midnightblue" internal-destination="xr5" id="fn5">5</fo:basic-link></fo:inline>.   Julie Christine Searsâ essay âBlack and White Rainbows and Blurry Linesâ (2003) argues for an evolution in Pynchonâs attitude towards homosexuality, and traces it from <fo:inline font-style="italic">Gravityâs Rainbow</fo:inline> to <fo:inline font-style="italic">Mason and Dixon</fo:inline>.</fo:block></fo:block><fo:block><fo:block space-before="4pt" id="d7e1102"><fo:inline><fo:basic-link font-family="sans-serif" font-size="85%" font-weight="normal" color="midnightblue" internal-destination="xr6" id="fn6">6</fo:basic-link></fo:inline>.   The connection to Orpheus has been noted widely in passing. Christopher K. Coffmanâs essay âBogomilism, Orphism, Shamanism: The Spiritual and Spatial Grounds of Pynchonâs Ecological Ethicâ is an in-depth reading which covers some of the same territory as this paper; however, we draw different conclusions as to the significance of the mythological and spiritual signifiers, as I will argue that these do not point solely, or even mostly, to the spatially-oriented, Earth-centered âOrphic Naturalismâ (Ã  la Eddins), but, at least in specific cases, to a path of transcendence.</fo:block></fo:block><fo:block><fo:block space-before="4pt" id="d7e1105"><fo:inline><fo:basic-link font-family="sans-serif" font-size="85%" font-weight="normal" color="midnightblue" internal-destination="xr7" id="fn7">7</fo:basic-link></fo:inline>.   The high degree of similarity between the Orphic and Pythagorean religions is represented by the willingness of many ancient and modern commentators to refer to a belief as âOrphico-Pythagoreanâ (Guthrie 216). However, the similarity between their ritual practices and basic tenets is contrasted by the extreme variance in cosmogonies: âThe Orphic cosmogony is mythical, expressed in terms of personal agents, of marriage and procreation. The world of Pythagoras is of divine origin, but he sought a rational, and in particular a mathematical explanation for itâ (Guthrie 219). In short, they are âfraternal, but not identicalâ (Guthrie 219), and both systems are represented throughout the text, with organizations and characters aligning along axes of Orphism/mythology (Bogomil convent, Cyprian) or Pythagoreanism/mathematics (T.W.I.T., Yashmeen, Kit).</fo:block></fo:block><fo:block><fo:block space-before="4pt" id="d7e1108"><fo:inline><fo:basic-link font-family="sans-serif" font-size="85%" font-weight="normal" color="midnightblue" internal-destination="xr8" id="fn8">8</fo:basic-link></fo:inline>.   Chosen/Passed over for salvation, in the Calvinist discourse of <fo:inline font-style="italic">Gravityâs Rainbow</fo:inline>.</fo:block></fo:block><fo:block><fo:block space-before="4pt" id="d7e1114"><fo:inline><fo:basic-link font-family="sans-serif" font-size="85%" font-weight="normal" color="midnightblue" internal-destination="xr9" id="fn9">9</fo:basic-link></fo:inline>.   The discussion of Slothrop as Orpheus constitutes an important part of several major Pynchon-related works, including Eddinsâs <fo:inline font-style="italic">The Gnostic Pynchon</fo:inline>, Humeâs <fo:inline font-style="italic">Pynchonâs Mythography</fo:inline>, and McClureâs <fo:inline font-style="italic">Partial Faiths.</fo:inline>
            </fo:block></fo:block><fo:block><fo:block space-before="4pt" id="d7e1126"><fo:inline><fo:basic-link font-family="sans-serif" font-size="85%" font-weight="normal" color="midnightblue" internal-destination="xr10" id="fn10">10</fo:basic-link></fo:inline>.   Obviously, this system, coupled with a withdrawal from society, would necessarily lead to the extinction of the order within a few generations; therefore there were different levels of orthodoxy among the followers. The âElectâ or âTrueâ lived âa monastic life of extraordinary asceticismâ while âthe great mass of the believers, called âHearersâ or âSoldiersâ, lived in the world under less rigorous rules, and to their meritorious deeds belonged the caring for the Elect that made their life of sanctification possibleâ (Jonas 232). The Soldiers were subject to reincarnation in a process of gradual perfectability until they achieved Elect status and could be freed from the cycle.</fo:block></fo:block><fo:block><fo:block space-before="4pt" id="d7e1129"><fo:inline><fo:basic-link font-family="sans-serif" font-size="85%" font-weight="normal" color="midnightblue" internal-destination="xr11" id="fn11">11</fo:basic-link></fo:inline>.   âTransmigration of the soul, passage of the soul from one body to another; <fo:inline font-style="italic">esp.</fo:inline> (chiefly in Pythagoreanism and certain Eastern religions) the transmigration of the soul of a human being or animal at or after death into a new body of the same or a different speciesâ (OED).</fo:block></fo:block><fo:block><fo:block space-before="4pt" id="d7e1136"><fo:inline><fo:basic-link font-family="sans-serif" font-size="85%" font-weight="normal" color="midnightblue" internal-destination="xr12" id="fn12">12</fo:basic-link></fo:inline>.   âPynchon seems to be setting up two exemplary paths of life: one the submissive worship and withdrawal from the world to monastic and convent life, the other action in the world, fighting the forces of capitalism, empire, slavery, expansion, and technologyâ (âReligiousâ 179). Hume sees a privileging of the second option in its connection to Catholic anarchism, which seems to overlook the violence inherent in the process; in the terms of my own argument, I would alternatively characterize it as a result of the existential nihilism that a gnostic universe, without cosmic or natural order, begets. As Hans Jonas, reading Nietzsche and Heidegger, explains, âA universe without an intrinsic hierarchy of being, as the Copernican universe is, leaves values ontologically unsupported, and the self is thrown back entirely upon itself in its quest for meaning and value. Meaning is no longer found but is âconferredâ. Values are no longer beheld in the vision of objective reality, but are posited as feats of valuation. As functions of will, ends are solely my own creationâ (321), and âthe countering of power with power is the sole relation to the totality of nature left for manâ (330). Violent anarchist activism, then, is a function of a fundamental understanding of the <fo:inline font-style="italic">absence</fo:inline> of God or divine order, and a recognition of the individualâs own responsibility for world-creation, not a Christian-inflected process.</fo:block></fo:block><fo:block><fo:block space-before="4pt" id="d7e1142"><fo:inline><fo:basic-link font-family="sans-serif" font-size="85%" font-weight="normal" color="midnightblue" internal-destination="xr13" id="fn13">13</fo:basic-link></fo:inline>.   This discussion of the historical aspects of Bogomilism is drawn from Janko Lavrinâs âThe Bogomils and Bogomilismâ (1929) and Dmitri Obolenkskyâs The <fo:inline font-style="italic">Bogomils: A Study in Balkan Neo-Manichaeism</fo:inline> (1948), primarily chapters 3-5.</fo:block></fo:block><fo:block><fo:block space-before="4pt" id="d7e1148"><fo:inline><fo:basic-link font-family="sans-serif" font-size="85%" font-weight="normal" color="midnightblue" internal-destination="xr14" id="fn14">14</fo:basic-link></fo:inline>.   I would argue that the negative significance of death in Pynchonâs other works proceeds from a primarily Christian eschatology and understanding of time; here death is not coded thusly.</fo:block></fo:block><fo:block><fo:block space-before="4pt" id="d7e1151"><fo:inline><fo:basic-link font-family="sans-serif" font-size="85%" font-weight="normal" color="midnightblue" internal-destination="xr15" id="fn15">15</fo:basic-link></fo:inline>.   Hume correctly notes Pynchonâs characterization of the movement of the Chums of Chance through the world as connected to the Catholic pilgrimage to various âstations of the crossâ; however, she fails to address the essentially Manichaean/Kabbalah/gnostic outward travel of the Chums in the final chapter, focusing instead on the Christian tonality of the word âgraceâ in the final line. In fact, the airshipâs final incarnation as a light-powered vessel connects it explicitly with the Manichaean âShip of Lightâ which is used to ferry the freed <fo:inline font-style="italic">pneuma</fo:inline> to a reunion with the divine essence (Jonas 230). Additionally, the shipâs ascent to âa series of remote stations high in unmeasured outer space, which together form a road to a destination,â along with the â<fo:inline font-style="italic">mnemonic frostbite</fo:inline>â (<fo:inline font-style="italic">AtD</fo:inline> 1084, original emphasis) together point to the penetration of the successive spheres by which the Archons have trapped the gnostic postulant, through which he must pass (by means of <fo:inline font-style="italic">gnosis</fo:inline>, or âknowledge of the wayâ), as well as the memory-loss accompanying this trial-and-error process of birth-death-rebirth.</fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:flow></fo:page-sequence></fo:root>